    body: "I see the world twice.\n\nThis is not a way of speaking. It is my eyes. One of them does not track the way the other one does. The light comes in along two roads. It arrives at two times, in two places, and the brain is left to make one picture out of two.\n\nMost of the time it does. The brain is good at this. It takes the two pictures and lays one over the other and slides them until the lines match, the way you slide two panes of glass together. You do not see the work. You see a table. You see a hand. You see one world, and it looks like everyone else's, and you go on.\n\nI went on a long time before I knew the work was being done. I thought every eye did this. I did not know there was an effort under the surface, holding the seam shut.\n\nThe seam holds until it doesn't.\n\nWhen I am tired it slips. Late, when I have not slept, the two pictures stop agreeing. The edge of the table doubles. A doorway shows two doorways, one a little to the right of the other. A light far off becomes two lights. I close one eye and the world goes flat and single. I open it and the world comes apart.\n\nIt slips when something matters too. That is the stranger part. When the stakes go up, when I have to do the thing right the first time, the body tightens and the eyes follow and the overlay loosens. The harder I look, the worse it gets. The thing I am trying to see is the thing that splits.\n\nI used to fight it. You can fight it for a while. You can tilt your head and find the one angle where the two pictures lie down together for a second. You can hold that angle until your neck hurts. You learn the tricks a body learns when it has to do on purpose what it used to do without thinking. There are a great many things I now do on purpose.\n\n[[NEEDS: concrete everyday tasks made deliberate by the eye and the hand — e.g. pouring, pool/curbs/stairs, threading something — confirm specifics]]\n\nThe hand is part of it too. [[NEEDS: specific lasting effect on the hand and how it shows up day to day]]\n\nI stopped fighting the eyes a while ago. I am not sure of the day. There was no morning I woke up and made peace. It was that fighting cost more than it bought. So I let the two pictures be two pictures. I looked at the seam instead of trying to close it.\n\nHere is what the seam taught me. The single world we think we see is not given to us whole. It is made. Something is always taking two offset pictures and reconciling them into one, and the work is so quiet and so constant that we take the result for the truth and forget there was ever any work. I know about the work because mine breaks down where I can see it.\n\nSo I see what is there. Not one world. Two of them. Slightly offset. Asking to be put together.\n\n[[NEEDS: the medical name for the eye condition / how the doctors described the tracking problem, if recorded]]\n\nThis is the plainest thing I can tell you and the whole book sits on it. When you have to put the world together by hand, you stop trusting that it comes that way. You watch the joins. You see where the two pictures don't line up, in a room, in a deal, in a face across a table, and you do the work of bringing them together. No one does it for you. The seam will not hold on its own.\n\nI do a lot of things now. I will get to them. There is the stage and there is the work and there is the system I built to keep my promises, and there is a man named Greg and a Sunday that belongs to us. There is a year I do not skip over, though I would like to. All of that is later.\n\nFor now there is only the fact, set down flat.\n\nI see the world twice. I have stopped trying to make it one.",
