    body: "I was thirteen the first time I walked across a room to show a stranger something with my hands.\n\nIt was a magic festival. [[NEEDS: where the festival was — city/country and year]]. There were tables and there were lights and there were men older than me doing things with cards and coins. The room was loud the way a room is loud when everyone in it wants the same thing. I stood at the edge of it. I had a deck in my pocket. I had practiced the move in the mirror until my fingers knew it without me.\n\nKostya was at one of the tables. [[NEEDS: what Kostya was doing/where he stood — table, performing, talking to others]]. I had watched him. I knew which one he was.\n\nI told myself I would go over. Then I did not. Then I told myself again.\n\nThe deck was warm from my pocket. I held it and did not move. You can do a card move alone in a room a thousand times and it costs you nothing. To do it for a man is to find out what it is worth. I knew that at thirteen. That is why my feet stayed where they were.\n\nThen I walked over.\n\nI do not remember the steps. I remember the table between us and the cards in my hand. I remember opening my mouth.\n\nMy voice shook.\n\nI asked him if I could show him a move.\n\n[[NEEDS: what Kostya said in reply — the actual words, if recorded]].\n\nI did the move. [[NEEDS: which card move he showed — the specific sleight or flourish]]. My hands did not shake the way my voice had. They had done it a thousand times in the mirror and they did it again now in front of a man, and it came out clean.\n\n[[NEEDS: Kostya's reaction to the move — what he did or said after]].\n\nThat is the whole of it. A boy crossed a room. He asked a man a question with a voice that would not hold still. He showed him a thing he had practiced alone.\n\nI have crossed bigger rooms since. I have stood on larger stages. [[NEEDS: confirm — which stages/credits to reference here, if any; bible lists real credits but specifics belong to Sebastian]]. None of them shook me the way that first walk shook me. By then I knew what the shaking was. The shaking was the cost. You pay it at the edge of the room, before you know what the thing is worth, and you walk anyway.\n\nI keep a deck in my pocket now. The hands still want it. They wanted it before I had words for what they wanted. A boy in Norway, far from any of this, with a mirror and a deck and no reason yet to believe the world had a place for it.\n\nI had no map for that room. [[NEEDS: how Sebastian got to the festival at 13 — who took him, how a boy in Norway found his way to a magic festival]]. I knew the men inside could do the thing I had been doing alone. I knew one of them was Kostya. I knew I had a move I had earned in the mirror.\n\nIt is always easier to stay at the edge. You keep the move. You never find out what it is worth. The mirror never tells you no.\n\nI did not stay at the edge.\n\nKostya is still my friend. [[NEEDS: how the friendship has carried from 13 to now — any specifics of the relationship over the years]]. He was one of the men I watched across a loud room when I was a boy. He is one of the men who texts me now. I do not think there is a clean line between those two things. The walk I made at thirteen did not end at his table. It is the same walk. I am still making it. I make it before every show. I make it before the calls I am afraid of. The voice does not shake anymore, or it shakes so quietly that only I can hear it, but it is the same voice, asking the same thing.\n\nCan I show you something.\n\nI learned the answer young. You walk across the room. You pay the shaking. You do the move clean.\n\nThe rest of my life has mostly been variations on that afternoon.",
