    published: false,
    body: "I was born in Norway.\n\nI do not say it often. When I do, people picture something. Snow. A fjord they saw in a photograph. They fill in the rest themselves, and I let them, because it is easier than the truth. The truth is that there are rooms in that country I have not walked back into for a long time.\n\nI was a boy there. [[NEEDS: the town or region in Norway where he grew up]]. I knew the streets the way a boy knows streets, with his feet and not their names. [[NEEDS: what kind of place it was — village, city, coast, inland]].\n\nThere was a house. [[NEEDS: the home — what it was like, who was in it]]. There were people in it who were mine. [[NEEDS: his parents — who they were, what they did]]. [[NEEDS: siblings, if any]]. I want to write them down plainly and I cannot. Not yet. The plain words are the ones that cost something, and I am still counting the cost.\n\nThe name on the papers from there is Midtvaage. That is the Norwegian name. It is the true one. The other name, the one on the company and the cards, I made later, on the other side. A man can have two names the way he can have two of most things. I did not plan it. I woke up one year and it was simply the weather I lived in.\n\n[[NEEDS: when and how magic first reached him in Norway, if it did, or whether it came only after]]. I did not know yet that I would walk toward it.\n\nSo that is the shape. A house. People I am not ready to name on the page. A boy with his own name, before the second one.\n\nAnd then I came to America.\n\nI will not pretend the crossing was a clean thing I can draw a line through. [[NEEDS: when he emigrated — the year, his age]]. [[NEEDS: why he left — what pushed, what pulled]]. [[NEEDS: how he came — alone, with family, the route]]. I know people leave for reasons and I know I had mine. I am telling you I do not have them lined up in a row to show you. I would rather say that than build a tidy reason out of nothing. A made reason is worse than no reason. It looks like the truth and it is not, and I have spent enough of my life learning to tell those two apart.\n\nWhat I can tell you is the offset. There is a country I came from and a country I am in, and they do not lie flat on top of each other. They are like the two images my eyes make when I am tired. The same world twice, a little apart, asking to be lined up. Norway is the one underneath. It sits under Orlando, under the work and the cards and the heat that never breaks. On certain nights I can feel exactly how far apart the two of them sit.\n\nI have not gone back much. [[NEEDS: whether and how often he returned to Norway between emigrating and 2026]]. There was a long stretch where going back was not a thing I let myself think about. There was too much in front of me that wanted doing, and a man can use the things in front of him as a wall against the things behind.\n\nThis is the half of the country I can write tonight. The boy, the house, the name. The crossing I can only gesture at, with my hand open, showing you the gaps instead of filling them.\n\nI would rather show you the gaps.\n\nThe other half — the cabin, the five hours of dark, the going back — comes later. I am not in a hurry to get there. The country you came from waits for you. It does not need you to optimize the trip. It is patient and it will still be there.\n\nI came from there. That much is true, and I will say it plainly, the way you say the things that matter most.\n\nI was born in Norway. I will go back.",
