    wordCount: 659,
    hasGaps: false,
    published: true,
    body: "People think magic is lying. It is not.\n\nA lie wants you to stop looking. Magic wants you to look harder. You give a man permission to be fooled, and he gives you permission back, and in that small trade something opens that does not open the rest of his week. He has a mortgage and a bad knee and a phone full of mail he has not answered. For ten seconds he forgets all of it. He leans in. His face changes. That is the work. Not the card. The face.\n\nI have done this more than twenty years. More years doing it than not. I started young, in a country where nobody around me did this, and I have done it long enough that the moves are quieter than my own breathing. The hands know. The hands have always known. What took the twenty years was learning what the hands were for.\n\nThe trick is the doorway. The wonder is what walks through.\n\nThe trick is the small thing I do with my fingers. Anyone can learn it. There are books. The wonder is not mine. It belongs to the man with the bad knee. I hold the door.\n\nWhat I do is make room for wonder in a room full of grown-ups. That is harder than it sounds. A child gives you wonder for free. A grown-up has spent years learning not to. He has been sold to. He has been fooled by people who wanted his money and his vote and his trust, and he has built a wall, and the wall is reasonable. I do not climb the wall. I knock. I show him my empty hands. I let him watch as close as he likes. Then, with his permission, for a few seconds, the wall comes down from the inside.\n\nI have had some rooms.\n\nI performed on the same stage Elvis stood on. I did not think about Elvis while I was on it. I thought about the deck and the light and the man in the third row. But it was the same stage. That is true, so I write it.\n\nI have worked rooms I am not at liberty to discuss. Fortune 500 companies. Federal government organizations. The circumstances are not mine to put in a book. I will say only that the wall in those rooms is taller, and that it comes down the same way it comes down at a child's birthday. A grown-up is a grown-up. The empty hands work the same everywhere.\n\nI am one of the magicians for the Orlando Magic. I do not say it to impress you. I say it because it is plain and it is true, and because there is a small joke in the name that I have never gotten tired of. A magician for the Magic. Some nights I work the floor before the game, close-up, the cards going while the crowd files in. A man stops with his beer and his kid and watches, and the kid watches the man more than the cards. That is the part I would not trade.\n\nI am a core cast member of a touring show. It has run at the Straz, in Tampa. It has run in London. It has run in Melbourne. I will not tell you what happens in it. A trick described is a trick killed. You should come see it.\n\nNone of that is the point. The stages and the rooms are the seen part, the part that goes on a poster. The point is what I learned standing in those rooms with my empty hands out. People want to believe. They are tired of being told not to. They will give you their guard if you give them a reason that does not cost them their dignity. That is the whole craft. The rest is finger work.\n\nThere was a year when the door shut on me. The floor was cold and there was no trick in my hands big enough. I will get to that year. It changed what I think the door is for.\n\nFor now I will say this. When I am tired, and my eye does the thing it does, the room separates into two rooms, slightly off from each other. I can still find the man in the third row in both of them. He is leaning in. He has forgotten his knee. His hands are open the way mine are open.\n\nI did not make the wonder. I never do.\n\nI held the door, and something walked through, and for a few seconds the room had two of us in it who believed.",
