    hasGaps: true,
    published: false,
    body: "The hand learns before you do.\n\nI started young. At thirteen I walked up to Kostya at a magic festival and asked if I could show him a card move. My voice shook. My hands did not. I had made them quiet by then. That is the first thing the hand learns. To be still when the rest of you is not.\n\nA deck of cards weighs almost nothing. You hold it a thousand hours and it weighs more. The cards wear soft at the corners. The faces go gray where the thumb rides. You break in a deck the way you break in a glove. Then you throw it out and start another. I have thrown out more decks than I can count. `[[NEEDS: how many decks per month/week he goes through; brand he uses]]`\n\nPeople think sleight is the fingers. It is the back of the hand and the wrist. The fingers finish what the wrist begins. You learn to move the small bones the way you learn a language. Slow, wrong, then less wrong, then without thinking. `[[NEEDS: specific sleights/moves he drilled — e.g. pass, palm, second deal, particular technique names]]`\n\nI drilled in front of a mirror. The mirror is honest. It shows you what the spectator sees, and that is the only thing that matters. You watch your own hands and you hate them. Then one day you watch and you do not see the move. That is the day the move is finished. The thing is there and then it is gone and your hand did not seem to do it.\n\nTwenty years of this. More years doing it than not. I have done the move more times than I have done almost anything. `[[NEEDS: his daily practice routine — when, how long, where he practiced over the years]]`\n\nYou practice in the dark. You practice with the television on and do not watch it, the hands working on their own. You practice at red lights. You practice in line at the store with your hand in your pocket, turning a coin over the knuckles, and nobody knows. The hand does it without you. That is the point. You give it twenty years and it does the work and leaves your mind free for the room.\n\nThe move is not the thing. The move is the door. I learned that late. For years I thought the work was the hands. The work is the hands so the hands disappear and you can watch the face of the person across the table. You want to see the moment the world they walked in with stops matching the world that is there. You can only see that if your hands need nothing from you. So you give the hands everything first. Twenty years. Then they ask for nothing and you are free.\n\nThere is a cost. After 2018 the hand does not always do what I tell it. `[[NEEDS: which hand; specific way the nerve damage shows up in card handling — e.g. a drop, a tremor, loss of a particular move]]` Some of the old moves I do not do anymore. Some I do slower. I had to learn certain things again with a hand that does not feel the cards the way it used to. The mirror is still honest. It shows me that too.\n\nI do not make a sermon of it. The hand learned the work for twenty years. Then I taught it some of the work twice. A man relearns his own hand. It happens.\n\nWhat I keep is this. The card does not care that I am tired. It does not care what year it is or what my body did. You shuffle. You cut. You turn the corners soft. The deck wears down and you start another, and the hand remembers everything you gave it, even the part the nerve took back. My hands still want a deck when the rest of me wants to stop. They have wanted one for twenty years. I let them have it. It is the cheapest quiet I own.\n\nThe wrist begins it. The fingers finish it. And across the table a grown person forgets, for a second, the world they walked in with. The hand made room for that. That was the only trick worth twenty years.",
