    hasGaps: true,
    published: false,
    body: "I was twenty-two.\n\nIt was 2018. I was uninsured. I knew it the way you know the weather. It was a fact I lived inside and did not look at.\n\nSomething was wrong. [[NEEDS: symptom that led to diagnosis; how found]]\n\nI waited. People wait. It is cheaper to wait.\n\nThen I went in. [[NEEDS: where treated]]\n\nThere were tests. There is a smell to those buildings. It is the same in every one. They put you in a gown and the gown does not close in the back. You sit on paper that tears when you move. The rooms are cold. The clock on the wall has a second hand and you watch it.\n\nA doctor said the word. The word was pineoblastoma. I had not heard it before. It is rare. It is in the brain. It is aggressive. It was in mine.\n\nThat is the flattest part of the story. A man in a coat says a word in a cold room and the world you had is gone. There is no music. There is the clock and the paper and the word.\n\nThey told me it was the kind they do not usually operate on. They said it plainly, the way you say a road is closed.\n\nI had the surgery anyway.\n\nI do not remember it. You are not meant to. They take the time out of you with the rest. [[NEEDS: where the surgery was done; length of hospital stay]]\n\nAfter came the radiation. You lie still. A machine moves around you and there is nothing to do but hold still, which is the one thing I have never been good at. The room is quiet. They leave and the door is heavy and the machine hums and you count. [[NEEDS: length of radiation course; treatment center]]\n\nThe recovery was long. [[NEEDS: length of recovery]]\n\nI will not say what it taught me. It taught me nothing. Cancer is not a teacher. It is not a gift. It did not come for a reason. What it did was end the version of me that thought time was a thing I owned. That is all it did. That is enough.\n\nThe body kept things. It still keeps them. There is nerve damage. One eye does not track the way the other does. A hand. [[NEEDS: which hand; specifics of the hand effect]] There are things I now do on purpose that other people do without thinking. I think about them and then I do them. It is slower. It works.\n\nThe hand was the one I minded. A magician lives in his hands. I had spent my life teaching them to lie clean, to be quiet, to do one thing while the eye believed another. Now my hand and my eye told me two different stories about one deck of cards, and I had to choose which to trust.\n\nI learned to trust the slower one.\n\nThen the bills came. They came in envelopes and they kept coming. The number got large. It passed five hundred thousand dollars. [[NEEDS: itemization or source of the debt figure, if any]]\n\nI was twenty-two and I owed more than half a million dollars and I had no insurance.\n\nThere were two ways out. One was to die. The other was bankruptcy. I looked at both for a while, the way you look at two roads, and neither was a road you would choose.\n\nI did not take either one.\n\nBecause I had been disabled by something life-threatening before I turned twenty-three, there was a program in Florida. It reached backward. It covered what had already happened. I enrolled in Medicare and Medicaid at twenty-two, which is not the age you are supposed to do that. The debt was wiped out. [[NEEDS: name of the Florida program; how he learned of it; who helped him enroll]]\n\nI made it to the other side.\n\nI say it plainly because it is the plainest true thing I know. Most of the people who get that word in that cold room do not get the program and do not get the surgery and do not make it to the other side. I did. There is no reason. I have stopped looking for one.\n\nWhat I carry now is not the scar, though there is a scar. [[NEEDS: location of the surgical scar]] It is the date. It is May 23. [[NEEDS: confirm what May 23 marks — diagnosis date, surgery date, or other]] It comes around every year whether I look at it or not, the way the second hand comes around the clock.\n\nI have not taken a real vacation since.\n\nFor a long time I thought that was discipline. It was not. I had learned what the cold room teaches and could not unlearn it. Time was not mine. It had never been mine. I had only thought it was, and the thinking was over.\n\nI was twenty-two. I lived. That was the year that ended one world. I held still and counted, and waited to see what I would build out of what was left.",
