    hasGaps: true,
    published: false,
    body: "The word is pineoblastoma.\n\nSay it once and let it sit. It does not get easier with use. I have said it many times and it still lands the same way. Flat. Like a stone set on a table.\n\nI was twenty-two. I was uninsured.\n\nIt is a tumor on the pineal gland. The gland sits deep. You cannot reach a thing like that the way you reach a thing on the surface. So they usually do not. It is rare. It is aggressive. It is the kind doctors do not usually operate on.\n\nI had the surgery anyway.\n\n[[NEEDS: the symptom/event that led to diagnosis; how it was found]]\n\n[[NEEDS: how the diagnosis was delivered — who, where, what was actually said]]\n\n[[NEEDS: where treated — hospital, city]]\n\nThen there was the radiation.\n\nYou go in for it. You lie still. They mark you and they leave the room and the machine does its work and you hear it more than you feel it. Then you go home, or to the place you are staying, and you wait, and you go back. You do this for a long time.\n\n[[NEEDS: length of treatment — weeks/months of radiation; where he stayed]]\n\nThe recovery was long. That is the true sentence. It was long.\n\nThe body comes back slow and it does not come back whole. I learned this in pieces. A nerve. The eye that does not track the way the other one does. The hand. There were things I had done all my life without thinking, and now I had to think about them. I had to send the thought down the wire and wait for the body to answer. Sometimes it answered late. Sometimes it answered wrong.\n\n[[NEEDS: which hand; specific motor effects and how they showed up day to day during recovery]]\n\nI will not tell you the cancer taught me anything. It did not. It is not a teacher and it did not come for a reason. People want it to mean something. They want you to come out the far side holding a lesson, so the thing they are afraid of will seem fair. It is not fair and it does not mean anything. What it did was end the version of me that thought time was a thing I owned.\n\nThat man thought he had a lot of it. He spent it like a man who had a lot of it. He is gone. I do not miss him much.\n\nI was twenty-two and I had no insurance. So while the body was being treated, the bills were being made. They came later. They came after, when I was supposed to be getting better. They were their own kind of weather.\n\nBut that is the next part. Before the bills, before any of it, there was the word.\n\nPineoblastoma.\n\nIt does not let you argue. It does not care what you had planned for the year. It does not care that you were young, or that at thirteen you had walked up to a man with your voice shaking to ask if you could show him something. None of that buys you anything. The word is set on the table and it is yours now and you are the one who has to pick it up.\n\nI picked it up. I did the surgery they did not usually do. I did the radiation. I came back slow and not all the way.\n\nI made it through. Not because I was brave. I was not brave. I was twenty-two and uninsured and the body was failing one wire at a time. I made it through the way you make it through anything. There was the next minute, and then there was the minute after that.\n\nThat is all surviving is. The next minute. You do the next minute. You do not think about the year. The year is too big and it is not yours anymore.\n\nThe word is pineoblastoma. I have said it enough now. I will set it down.",
