    wordCount: 689,
    hasGaps: true,
    published: false,
    body: "I built a system because I kept losing things.\n\nNot big things at first. A name. A date. The thing a man told me on the phone that mattered to him more than the policy did. I would write it on paper and the paper would go somewhere. A week would pass and the man would call back and I would not have it. He would hear that in my voice. I heard it too.\n\nSo I built something. Not routines. Routines are what you tell yourself you will do. This was made.\n\nIt is software and notebooks and calendars, wired so they talk. There is a daily note. Each morning it carries yesterday forward. What I said I would do. Who I owed something to. What is still open. I do not have to remember the day before. The day before is on the page, waiting, in my hand and in the machine's.\n\nThere are agents now. Small programs that watch the parts I can't. My eye does not track right. My hand is slower at some things than it was. There are hours when I am tired and the two images pull apart and I lose the edges of things. The agents do not get tired. One watches the calendar. One watches the mail. One keeps a list of people and what is owed to each of them and how long it has been. When something goes stale, it tells me. It does not care that I am tired. That is the point of it.\n\nI did not build it to sell. People ask me that. They see the tools on the table and think there is a product under it. There isn't. I built it for one person. The alternative was to keep losing the things I had promised not to lose.\n\nHere is what it is for.\n\nA man calls me about a plan. [[NEEDS: any real detail about a specific client — when, what plan, what he said]] At the end he says a thing, quiet, almost as an aside. I write it down. The agent files it against his name. Three weeks later the note comes back to me before the morning is half gone. I call him. I am not calling about the policy. I am calling about the thing he said three weeks ago. He had not expected me to remember. I had not remembered. The machine had. To him it is the same. To him a promise was kept.\n\nNo one claps. It is the smallest kind of wonder there is. It is the kind I trust most.\n\nThe other one is closer to home.\n\nMy mother needs a wrist wrap. [[NEEDS: which wrist / what the injury or condition is]] She said it once, in passing, the way people say a thing they do not expect you to carry. [[NEEDS: when and where she told me about the wrist]] I am no good at this. By evening I would have lost it the way I lost everything before. But I had put it in the system, and the system does not let go.\n\nIt is late. I am in bed. The body will not power down the way other people's do. It never has, not since. I lie there with my eyes open and the dark is full of all the open things. Then the note surfaces. The wrist wrap. My mother. I see it on the small screen, plain, and I order it then, in the dark, with my thumb. [[NEEDS: how the wrist wrap was sent or given to her — mailed, brought, etc.]]\n\nThat is it. A man does not lose his mother's wrist wrap between dinner and sleep. He used to. Now he doesn't.\n\nIt took years. It is still taking years. I add a piece and a month later the piece is doing work I never told it to do, and I find I have been leaning on it without noticing. That is how I know it is real. The things you lean on without noticing are the ones holding you up.\n\nI run a business. I write this book. I do a show every other weekend. Anyone wired the way I am can pour himself into a thing until it eats the others. The trick is that none of them does. The show does not eat the business. The book does not eat my mother's wrist. The system holds the room so each one can have its hour and then let go.\n\nThe wiring is not the wonder. The wonder is the room the wiring makes. A room where a promise from three weeks ago is still standing when a tired man walks back into it.\n\nI am not in a hurry. The system is. It carries the hurry so I don't have to. It watches what I can't, and it remembers the things I promised not to lose. That is what I built it for.",
